'''Yasin Abbas Ayari''' ({{langx|ar|ياسين عباس عياري}}; {{IPA|sv|ˈjɑː.sɪn aˈjɑː.rɪ}}; born 6 October 2003) is a Swedish professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for {{English football updater|Brigh&HA}} club [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] and the [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden national team]].

== Club career ==
Ayari began playing football with the youth academy of [[Råsunda IS|Råsunda]] at the age of 6, before moving to [[AIK Fotboll|AIK]] around the age of 8.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.svenskfotboll.se/nyheter/landslag/2019/4/p16-ft-ayari/|title=Yasin Abbas Ayari om landslagsdebuten|website=svenskfotboll.se|date=25 April 2019 }}</ref>

=== AIK ===
Ayari made his professional debut with AIK in a 2–2 [[Allsvenskan]] tie with [[IF Elfsborg|Elfsborg]] on 6 December 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fotbollsthlm.se/aik/17-aring-fran-start-i-aik-har-ar-laget-mot-elfsborg/|title=17-åring från start i AIK – här är laget mot Elfsborg|date=6 December 2020}}</ref> On 22 October 2021, he signed his first professional contract with AIK until 31 December 2025.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aikfotboll.se/nyheter/a-lagskontrakt-for-yasin-ayari-2021-10-22|title=A-lagskontrakt för Yasin Ayari|website=AIK Fotboll}}</ref>

=== Brighton and Hove Albion ===
On 30 January 2023, Ayari signed a contract with [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] until June 2027.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3041881/albion-sign-yasin-ayari-from-aik|title=Albion sign Yasin Ayari from AIK|website=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|date=30 January 2023|access-date=30 January 2023|archive-date=30 January 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230130232337/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3041881/albion-sign-yasin-ayari-from-aik|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Ayari made his ''Albion'' debut on 19 March, coming on as a 78th minute substitute replacing [[Alexis Mac Allister]] in the 5–0 [[2022–23 FA Cup|FA Cup]] quarter-final win over [[EFL League Two|League Two]] side [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3116523/wembley-next-as-albion-cruise-into-fa-cup-semi-finals|title=Wembley next as Albion cruise into FA Cup semi-finals|website=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|date=19 March 2023|access-date=19 March 2023|archive-date=13 April 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240413163837/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3116523/wembley-next-as-albion-cruise-into-fa-cup-semi-finals|url-status=dead}}</ref> He made his first Premier League start on 28 May, in his third league appearance, where he was substituted at half time of the 2–1 away defeat at [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in the last game of the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3490388/deniz-enjoys-another-away-day-but-albion-lose-finale|title=Deniz enjoys another away day but Albion lose finale|publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion|date=28 May 2023|access-date=28 May 2023|archive-date=28 May 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230528234326/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3490388/deniz-enjoys-another-away-day-but-albion-lose-finale|url-status=dead}}</ref>

On 26 April 2025, Ayari scored his first goal for Brighton in a 3–2 victory over [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] at [[Falmer Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Brighton 3–2 West Ham (Apr 26, 2025) Game Analysis |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/704610 |access-date=2025-04-26 |publisher=ESPN |language=en}}</ref>

==== Coventry City (loan) ====
On 21 August 2023, Ayari joined [[EFL Championship]] club [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] on loan.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Coventry sign Brighton midfielder Ayari on loan |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66576134 |access-date=2023-08-21}}</ref>

==== Blackburn Rovers (loan) ====
On 5 January 2024, Ayari joined fellow [[EFL Championship]] club [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] on a loan deal until the end of the 2023–24 season.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Ayari arrives! |language=en-GB | work=Blackburn Rovers FC | url=https://www.rovers.co.uk/news/2024/january/05/ayari-arrives-/ | access-date=2024-01-05}}</ref>

==International career==
Born in Sweden to parents from Tunisia and Morocco, Ayari was a youth international for Sweden.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Abeid|first=Mahdi|url=https://www.alaraby.co.uk/sport/موهبة-تونسية-تفرض-وجودها-في-عملاق-السويد-وتظفر-بعقدها-الأول|title=موهبة تونسية تفرض وجودها في عملاق السويد وتظفر بعقدها الأول|website=alaraby.co.uk|language=ar|date=23 October 2021}}</ref> Ayari made his full international debut for [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]] in a friendly game against [[Finland national football team|Finland]] on 10 January 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |date=10 January 2023 |title=Avslöjar: Premier Leagues succélag visar intresse för AIK-talang |url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/a/RGm9ea |access-date=10 March 2023 |website=Aftonbladet |language=sv}}</ref>

On 12 May 2026, Ayari was named in the Sweden squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-05-12 |title=Mystiskt inlägg efter petningen |url=https://www.expressen.se/sport/fotboll/landslaget/har-ar-sveriges-trupp-till-fotbolls-vm-2026/ |access-date=2026-05-15 |website=www.expressen.se |language=sv}}</ref>

==Personal life==
His mother Amina works for AIK, and his brother [[Taha Ayari|Taha]], born 2005, plays for AIK and has had a trial at [[Feyenoord]].{{citation needed|date=October 2025}}

